<TITLE> UN chief condemns 'acts of violence' </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 28 (bdnews24.com)  United Nations Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon has condemned the "brutal acts of violence," during the two-day mutiny by members of the Bangladesh Rifles. Bodies were still being unearthed from shallow graves at BDR headquarters on Saturday, three days after the revolt by border guards against military officers. Among the dead were the BDR chief Maj Gen Shakil Ahmed and his wife, and his second in command. "The Secretary-General is distressed at the mounting death toll in the violent two-day mutiny," said a statement released by Mr Ban's spokesperson in New York on Friday. "He condemns such brutal acts of violence and extends his deepest sympathy to the victims, to their families and to the people and Government of Bangladesh," said the statement. The Dhaka UN office also extended its most profound sympathies to all those affected by these "barbarous acts of violence", in a statement. "We hope all will unite to help the recovery from this national tragedy in a spirit of peace and national oneness, for the greater good of the nation," said the statement. A bloody two-day mutiny by rebellious border guards that began Wednesday left a death toll of 77, mostly officers, as more bodies were unearthed on Saturday . More than 70 officers were still reported 'missing'.
